\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b1 Parasites.}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~The intestinal canal is infested by several forms of entozoa, among which may be found the following:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Ascaris lumbricoides}{\f0\fs24\b0 ; the common round worm, six to ten inches in length. It may be single or in large numbers.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Oxyuris vermicularis}{\f0\fs24\b0 ; a small white worm, measuring from two to four lines in length, and found only in the large intestines, and mainly in the lower part of the rectum, where they may be present in large numbers.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Trichina spiralis.}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~This parasite is found in the small intestine, and only in its adult form. It measures from less than a line, to two lines in length. The embryos penetrate the walls of the intestine, and finally locate in the muscles, where they remain encapsulated. If a portion of this muscle is eaten by another animal, the larv\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u230\'E6 again become active,\~}{\f0\fs24\b0 1}{\f0\fs24\b0 60and acquiring the mature sexual form, reproduce, the young embryos again migrating to the muscles.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Tricocephalus dispar.}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Found only in the head of the colon, and measures one and a-half to two inches in length; neck long, and body of male covered with wart-like appendages on one side.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Distoma lanceolatum.}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Flat, lancet-shaped, and transparent, a-half inch long, one-quarter wide. Rarely found in upper portion of small intestines, natural habitat appearing to be in the bile passages.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Of tapeworms, the following varieties may be found:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 T\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u230\'E6nia solium.}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Head about the size of a pin-head, and furnished with sucking disk and double row of hooks; neck long and narrow; body flat and jointed, each segment about a-half inch in length; body may be from ten to fifty or more feet in length.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 T\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u230\'E6nia mediocanellata.}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Head truncated and destitute of hooks; body jointed and of great length.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 T\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u230\'E6nia flavopuncta.}{\f0\fs24\b0 \~Very rare. Yellow spot at the middle of each joint.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i1 Bothriocephalus latus}{\f0\fs24\b0 , (broad tapeworm.) Head long, unarmed; neck inconspicuous; body composed of about two thousand joints; mature joints broader than long.}
